Date: Thu 23 Nov 2017
Source: OIE, WAHID (World Animal Health Information Database), weekly disease information [edited] http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapFullEventReport&reportid=25278


Tilapia lake virus disease (TiLV), Philippines
----------------------------------------------
Information received on 23 Nov 2017 from Dr Enrico Garzon, assistant secretary for livestock, Bureau of Animal Industry, Department of Agriculture, Quezon City, Philippines

Summary
Report type: immediate notification (final report)
Date of start of the event: 16 May 2017
Date of confirmation of the event: 29 Jun 2017
Date event resolved: 15 Sep 2017
Reason for notification: emerging disease
Morbidity: 8/33.7 per cent
Mortality: 8/33.7 per cent
Zoonotic impact: no
Causal agent: Tilapia lake virus (TiLV)

New outbreaks (1)
Summary of outbreaks, total outbreaks: 1
Outbreak 1: Bulacan, Dampol 2nd , Pulilan, Bulacan
Date of start of the outbreak: 16 May 2017
Outbreak status: resolved on 15 Sep 2017
Epidemiological unit: pond
Water type: fresh water
Population type: farmed
Production system: semi-closed
Total animals affected:
Species / Morbidity / Mortality / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Killed and disposed of / Slaughtered
Tilapia (_Oreochromis niloticus_) / 34 per cent / 34 per cent / 300 000 / 101 363 / 101 363 / 0 / 0

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: unknown or inconclusive
Epidemiological comments: an unexplained daily mortality of tilapia fingerlings was observed in the nursery pond of a private farm after stocking on [Tue 16 May 2017]. Elevated mortality after 15 days reached about 25 per cent. Affected fish showed abdominal distension and bulging of the eyes. On [Wed 31 May 2017] samples were collected and submitted at the Fisheries Biotechnology Center (FBC) Mu√±oz, Nueva Ecija. Semi-nested RT-PCR exhibited positive results using reported Tilapia Lake Virus (TiLV) primers. Other samples submitted to National Fisheries Laboratory - Fish Health of the Bureau of Fisheries and Aquatic Resources also showed positive results by insulated isothermal PCR (iiPCR). The amplified segment 3 of the viral gene has 94-95 per cent nucleotide similarity to Israel TiLV strain. The movement of fingerlings from the affected pond is restricted and monitored. Results of the last 2 samplings showed negative for TiLV using iiPCR.

Control measures
Measures applied: movement control inside the country, surveillance outside infected and/or protection zone, surveillance within infected and/or protection zone, screening, traceability, quarantine, disinfection, vaccination permitted (if a vaccine exists), no treatment of affected animals

Measures to be applied: no other measures

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type / Species / Test / Test date / Result
Fisheries Biotechnology Center (Local laboratory) / Tilapia (_Oreochromis niloticus_) / reverse transcription - polymerase chain reaction (RT-PCR) / 24 Jun 2017 / Positive
National Fisheries Laboratory (National laboratory) / Tilapia (_Oreochromis niloticus_) polymerase chain reaction (PCR) / 29 Jun 2017 / Positive

Future reporting
The event is resolved. No more reports will be submitted.

[The location of the outbreak can be seen on the interactive map included in the OIE report at the source URL above.]

